{"/service/ndnp/mb/batch_mb_basil_ver01/data/sn83020847/00517170835/1945083001/0489.xml":{"full_text":"Big Lack of Homes for Men\nPaying S2O-S4O Per Month\nNHA Administrator Says Greatest Housing Need Today\nIs for Those in That Bracket Who Would Buy or\nRent Low-Cost Homes\nWashington, Aug. 23\u2014(AP)\u2014The\ngovernment's top housing expert said\ntoday the greatest need is a home\nfor the man whose pocketbook can\nstand only S2O to S4O a month.\n.John B. Blandford, Jr., National\nMoulting agency administrator, thinks\nprivate enterprise will provide homes\nfor the S4O-plug class and the gov\nernment low-rent program will take\ncare of the S2O-mlnus class.\nPotential Market\nBut Blandford, who supervised the\nwar housing program, said in an in\nterview; \u201cThe big gap is the market\nbetween S2O and S4O, or thereabout.\nIt represents a potential added mar\nket of 400.000 houses a year and must\nbe developed if we are to reach and\nhold a construction rate of 1,250,000 I\nhouses yearly.\u201d\nBlandford has a two-fold plan to\nstimulate interest in this type of'\ndwelling; An extension of mortgage\ninsurance to help builders and guar\nanteed income to large investors in\nrent projects. Here\u2019s the story:\n1. A man buying a home usually\ncan only make a small down pay-\nment. He borrows the remainder on i\na mortgage. This postpones full own\nership until he pays out the balance\nrepresented on the mortgage loan,\nplus interest over the years.\nThe Federal Housing administration\n|FHA), an agency under Blandford's\nNHA, already insures a mortgage (to\nsome individual or company) on\nhomes built to NHA specifications.\nThe insurance guarantees io the,\nmortgage-lender that the buyer will\npay out.\nThe NHA Viewpoint\nThe plan NHA now is considering\nIs something new. That is, a pledge\nto the builder, two to three years in\nadvance, concerning the amounts it\nwill insure the mortgages on the\nhomes he plans to build. Blandford\nsays the builders, with these commit\nments. could borrow const ruction\nmoney cheaper, thus reducing costs.\nThey could plan operations far ahead.\nent in the S2O\ncategory a \u2022yield\" insurance plan\nIs contemplated.\nIt would guarantee to large in-\nvestors like a big insurance company,\na regular income (yield) for 30 or 40\nyears on houses they build to rent.\nA yield of 3 to 3% per cent is planned\nwith up to M per cent of that yield\nwithheld against possible government\nloss on its guarantee.\nThe yield insurance plan already\nis before Congress. It is in an over-\nall housing program proposed by Sen\nator Wagner (D-NY). on which hear\ning are slated soon after Congress\nreconvenes.\nThe mortgage insurance extension\n\u2014noted in No 1 above \u2014may be worked\nout without new legislation.\nSUGAR SUPPLY LOW\nFOR REST OF YEAR\nAmerican Stockpile Shows\nSlow Improvement, but\nPicture Is Not Bright\nWashington. Aug. 22 (AP) For\nJhe present, there will be no more\nsugar to sweeten the fruits of victory.\nA picture of slow improvement in\nthe American supply, vague as to the\ntime when the national sweet-tooth\nwill get back to Its prewar quota,\nwas drawn today by several author!-\nties.\nThere was agreement that no\nmarked increase in present short ra\ntions is in sight for the remainder of\nthis year.\nThe day produced these develop\nments in the sugar sector:\nI. Price Administrator Chester\nBowles said controls on sugar, fats and\noils would be the last to be dropped.\nIt was learned that OPA plans to an\nnounce shortly that the new sugar\nstamp valid September 1 will main\ntain the current, ration \u2014five pounds\nfor four months.\n2. Secretary of Agriculture Ander-,\nson predicted more sugar for the na\ntion in 1946 from increased Cuban\nand domestic sugar beet production.\n3. The bureau of agriculture ex-!\npreyed belief that several years may.\npass before the world gets all the\nxtigar it wants.\n4. Senator Wherry (R-Neb.) advo\ncated a sls per ton incentive to beet\nsugar producers to increase that sup-\nEASTHAMPTON FIRM\nBOUGHT BY TEXTRON\nNationally Known Textile\nCorporation to Take Over\nHampton Company in Big\nTransaction\nKasihampton. Apr. 28\u2014The Hamp-\u2019\ntnh com pans of thia town, textile\nmanufacturers. was reported tonlghi\nto have been sold to the Textron cor\nporation in what la believed to be on\nof the largest transactions in this\narea in many years. A branch of the!\nTextron company now operates here j\nend Is one of many branches of one\nof the largest textile manufacturing,\ncorporations In the United States.\nActive In War Work\nNo official confirmation of the deal\nCould be obtained from persons aaso-i\nelated with the Hampton mills but Itj\nhas been known for some time that\nsuch a transaction has been Immi\nnent. The Hampton company Is one\nof the largest local mills and has been\nengaged during the war In the manu\nfacture of textile product^ Important\nto the air forces of the army and\nnavy.\nThe McConnell family of North\nampton has been prominently asso\nciated with the company and Archie\n.McConnell Is vice-president and as\nBlatant treasurer while Robert Mc-\nConnell owns a portion of the com\npany's stock.\nIt was reliably reported that mans\nofficers of the company have resigned\nfrom their positions since the com\npletion of the transaction.\nLOANS ON POTATOES\nAVAILABLE IN STATE\nBoston. Aug. 25\u2014(AP>\u2014Massachu\nsetts farmers may receive commodity\n\u2018Credit loans on their late crop pota\ntoes again this year tinder the gov.\nernment's 1946 price support program\nArthur Bardwell, chairman of\nthe Massachusetts state potato com\nmittee. tonight said that growers,\ngrowers' associations, and dealers\ncertified by county AAA committees\nI as having agreed to pay the price\nsupport equivalent to growers are\neligible for loans which will be avail\nable starting September 16.\nPenicillin has been used with good\nL results for th etreatment of crown\ngall, sometimes called plant cancer.\nFINANCIAL\nINDUSTRIALS OPEN\nSTRONG BUT SKID\nON PROFIT-TAKING\ni Rails End On Down Side\n$75,000,000 Offer lor\nPullman Business Seen as\nGood Omen\nWall Street Correspondence\nOf The Republican\nI New York, Aug. 28\u2014Industrial\nstocks opened active and strong with\nseme new higha made in the early\ntrading but the market then on\n'smaller volume ran into some profit\n.taking which was natural after the\n'recent violent advances. Industrials\nclosed up .36. Rails were lower on the\nhourly averages, closing down .28.\nToday's announcement that a syn\ndicate headed by Otis A Co., invest\nment bankers of Cleveland, has made\n[an offer to buy the sleeping ear\nI business of Pullman for $75,000,000\nI tells the same amazing story being\nunfolded by the slock market.\nWhen industry in the early sum\nmer of 1940 began to switch produc\ntion to fit in with the nation\u2019s de\nfense program, a switch that resulted\nin a miracle performance and the\ndownfall of Hitlerism and the same\nsort of thing that was going on in\nJapan, leaders of industry and finance\nrealised that when peace came, an\nother crisis would have to be faced in\nreconversion. Up until very recently it\nwas agreed that reconversion would\nbring about, stockmarketwise, at least\na temporary downward readjustment\nof prices.\nWhat is being witnessed in the\nstock market, however, is anything\nbut what was expected. Up to the\n[close of the market, yesterday prices\nof industrial shares advanced for five\n[consecutive days with a net gain of\n8.85 points.\nTrading in the stock market means\ncash placed on the line. In yester\nday\u2019s market, made up largely of\n\u2018trading m high-priced shares believed\ni to have good postwar prospects, more\n(rash was placed on the line than for\nany session this year.\nIf the story the stock market is\ntelling resulted from something like\na Gallup poll registering the opinion\n;of millions of individual citizens the\nstory would run something like this:\nMoney is being placed on the line in\ni the stock market because individual\ncitizens are making a bet in their\nbelief that the government is going\nto give business more of a chance\nthan it has had since the collapse in\n1929 of the boom of the 1920'5; that\n1946 will see a substantial reduction\nIn the wartime excess profits tax cor-\nporations have been paying; that\nthere is an unprecedented amount of\nunsatisfied consumer demand with\nmore spending money in the hands\nof rhe public than ever before; that\nin taking care of the domestic de\nmand for civilian goods and that of\nforeign countries, this country has\nahead of it the biggest business in its\nI history.\nWhat is happening in the stock\nmarket is not the expected downward\nreconversion adjustment of prices but\nI unexpected upward readjustment of\nprices.\nAnd the story the stock market has\nbeen felling is the same as th eone\nbehind today s eiews that a syndicate\nhad made an offer to buy the sleeping\ncar business of Pullman for $75,000,-\n000.\nIn July of 1940 the government\n(brought an antitrust suit against Pull\nman. charging that through control\nof its sleeping car service used by\nthe railroads it forced the railroads\nto buy equipment which the company\nalso was manufacturing. The result\nof this suit charging violation of the\nSherman act was that in April of\n1943. Pullman was ordered by the\n[court to separate its sleeping car\nbusiness from its equipment manu\nfacturing business. Following this\ndecree Pullman offered to sell its\nsleeping car business to the railroads.\nBut the offer was not accepted. The\nrailroads were not able to agree\namong themselves. New York Cen\ntral. for instance, thought the rail\nroads should as a whole buy Pull\nman's sleeping car business and op\nerate it jointly. Pennsylvania, be\nlievlng there was no profit in the\nsleeping car service, refused lb have\nI anything to do with Pullman's offer.\nThat is where the matter stood\nwhen Otis Co came along with a\nsyndicate offer io purchase the busi\nness. Looking ar the detailed earn-\nI Ings figures published annually by\nPullman, what Pennsylvania, and\nsome other railroads saw was very\n[heavy depreciation deductions annual\nly for the upkeep of the sleeping car\nequipment. To go back no further\n'than 10 years in the annual reports.\nfor 1943 the book value per share of i\nPullman's equipment and plant, after\nallowing for depreciation, was $44.40.\nby the end of 1942 it was only $33.95.\nBut In the meantime net working\n[capital of Pullman was increasing\nJ from $15.25 a share to $26.45. Equip-\nI ment without being replaced was be\ning converted into cash, being liqui\ndated because Pullmans mangement\n[lacked the imagination Otis and their\n'associates are displaying. The Cleve\nland investment banker ran see\nmoney spent for new equipment giv\ning the public better sleeping car\nservice than it ever before has had;\nthat the public will be willing and\nready to pay for that service: that\nthe sleeping car business can b^\nmade a profitable business.\nWhat Otis and his associates have\nin mind, if their offer is approved by\nthe court and accepted by Pullman\nshareholders, is to form a separate\ncompany and sell the stock to the\nnubile. That is what J. P. Morgan\n(did at the beginning of this century\nwhan there was great industrial ex\npansion in buying Carnegie. Steel\n[stock os the foundation for the Unit\n,ed States Steel corporation. It was\nwhat was done later In Genera! Mo\ni tors when the automobile industry\nwas In its long baby clothes.\nIt is necessary to go back to the\n1920 s. before the first and second\nJ depression, to find a group of men\nhaving enough faith u the general\nbusiness outlook to do what members\nof the Otis syndicate are proposing.\nIt is the same story the stock mar\nket has been telling.\nR. U BARNUM.\nABBOTT DIVIDENOS\nChicago. Aug, 23 (AP) Abbott\nLaboratories today announced pay\ni ment of a 15 cent extra dividend on\ni its common stock for the seventh\nconsecutive quarter. The, directors\nalso declared a regular quarterly div\nidend of 40 cents a share on th*\ncommon stock payable September 29\nto stockholders of record September\nI 6. 1945, and $1 a share on the pre\nferred stock payable Ooiober 15 to\nstockholders of record wtober L\nTHE SPRINGFIELD WEEKLY REPUBLICAN: SPRINGFIELD, MASS.: THURSDAY, AUGUST 30, 1945\nNEW YORK STOCK MARKET\nSale of Stocks\nNew York Stock exrhange .1,2(10,000\nNew York Curb exchange .100,000\nBoston Stock exchange 16,4*0\nNot\nSales in 100's High Low Close Chg\nA\n18 ACF-81111 Moi 14% 14% 14% F\n9 Acme St I 29 28% 28\n7 Adams Exp 15% 15% 15%-\n1 Adams-Millis 40 40 40\nI Addressog-Mull ,27% 27% 27%\n21 Air Reduction 45% 44% 45\n20 Alaska Juneau 7 6% 7\n59 Alleghany Corp 4% 4% 4%\n7 Do pf 4\u00ab 47% 47% I\n12 Alleg Lud Sil .13% 32 %33\n3 Al Chem 4 Dye .188% 158% 1\u00ab8%\n4 Allied Kid 17% 17% 17%-\n12 Allied Milla 29% 29 29\n30 Allied Sirs 32% 30% 31\n27 Allls-Ch Mfg 5(1% 49% 50\n6 Allls-Ch Mfg pf 126 125 120 2\nID Alpha P ('em 29% 28% 28%\n2 Amal Leather 5% 5% 5%\n17 Am Ag h Del 33% 3.3 3::\n4 Arn Airlines 67 60% 67\n3 Am Rank Note 30 29% 30\n9Am Bosch 17% 17% 17% J- Vs\n7 Am Brake Shoe 45% 45 45%\n25 Am CabieA\u00dfad 11% 11% 11%\n4Am Can 101 100% 101 1\n.40 Am Can pf ....190% 190% J9(t%\n17 Am Car Fdy 58% 57% 58%+\n2Am Car F pf 114 114 114 +l%\n10 Am Ch i Cable 32 31% 31%+\n.50 Am C A C pf .119% 119% 119% 1\u00bb4\n1.30 Am Chicle 133% 133% 133%+\n2 Am Crystal Sug 22% 22% 22%\n.10 Do pf 108 IDB 108\n11 Am Distill 38 37 37%\u2014 i\n4 Am Encaus Tilg 7 H% 6%\n3 Arn Export L 39 38% 38%\u2014\n26 Am F P 5 4% 5\n11 Do 2pf 27% 27 27%+ I\n1 Arn Hide A L 7% 7% 7%\n8 Am. Home Prod 79% 78% 79%+\n2 Ain Ice 8% 8% 8%\n25 Am Internal 10% 10% 10%+\n4 Am Invest 111 10% 10% 10%\n52 Am Loco mot 36% 3.'>% 36%\n19 Am MA Fdy 28% 27 V 2 28%\n18 Am M&Met 13% 12% 13%+\n1 Am Metal 27% 27% 27%\n.60 Am News Co 46% 46% 46%+\n36 Am Pow&Lt 7% 7 7%+\n6 Do $6 pf 79 78% 78%\n12 Do $5 pf 71 70