psrhd 7% 7%\n16 US For Sec 17% 16%\nJOUS A For S pf KH\u00bb V* T 1\n.3 US Freight 2\u2019%\n211 S Gvp\u00abmn 97 9?\n2US HoffmanMch 18% 18% 1\u00ab%\nI UR Hoff W pf 50% m% 50% r\nFINANCIAL\nWar Workers in No Hurry\nTo Obtain Different Jobs\nSurvey Reveal* Many Refute to Take Work Paying\nLett Waget Some Do Not Intend to Work\nCHRYSLER\u2019S CLIMB\nSPURS INDUSTRIALS\nTO SET NEW MARK\nGroup Advances 2.06 to Lat\nest Recovery High; Rails\nFollow at Slower Pace\nSeat Brings $68,000\nWall Street Corre.pondenee\nOf The Repnhlksn\nNew York, Aug. 27 Industrial\nstocks opening strong and active un\nder rhe leadership of Chrysler, which\nagain made a new recovery high,\nhourly went into a new average re\ncovery high, closing at or near the\nday> best, up 2.08. Rails followed\nindustrials but at a slower pace, the\ngain for the day being .75.\nTwo Stock exchange seats changed\nhands today at $67,000 and SBB,OOO.\nlup S7OOO and SBQOO from the last\ntransaction.\nA week ago today the closing av\nerage price of industrial shares was\n[down 1.27 but for the next four con\nsecutive days up to the closing last\nweek there was a net advance of\n,6.78 points to a new recovery high.\nRails closed week ago today down\n1.57 and then advanced for four con\nsecutive days with a ne) gain of 3.13\npoints. But at last week s close, rails\nwere still 845 below their recovery\nhigh\nUnder the old Dow theory, if the\nprice trend of the market is upward,\nrhe new recovery high made by in\nduatrials at the close of last w^ek\nshould be confirmed by a new recov\nery high for rails. Throughout The\nbull market starting from The April,\n1942. wartime low. rails and indus\ntrials invariably followed the Dow\ntheory as they did in other bull mar\nkers with the same thing true in re\nverse in bear markets. Should rails\nbe expected to make a new recov\nery high in the not distant future?\nWail street's bear guess today is\nthat for the period of reconversion by\nindustry less importance, stockmar\nket wise. should be attached to th*\nDow theory No one can tell as far\nas industrial companies as a whole\nare concerned how long the reconver\nsion period will last. Estimates have\nbeen that the industrial production\nindex should decline monthly for the\nremainder of 1945 and probably for\nthe first quarter of 1946 after which\nthere should be slow recovery for a\nfew months from rhe bottom. But\nthe government's war activities since\nJapan asked for peace have been\nchopped off. Reconversion by indus\ntrial companies so far has moved\nmuch faster than was expected- If\nthat continues the bottom and the\nupturn in the industrial production I\nindex from the reconversion period\nlow will come much sooner than was\nexpected.\nAs for industrial stocks, the best\nopinion in the financial district here\n[today is that during the reconversion\nperiod ihe price movement will be\nirregular; that ihe sto k of some\n\u2019companies that have had. during the\nwar. larger earnings than in peace\ntime will decline, while others with\na record of making more prefits in\n'peacetime than during the war will\n\u2022advance. What Chrysler shares re\n[cently have been doing affords a good\nexample on one side, with the other\nside illustrated by what has hap\npened in the shares of companies\nmanufacturing airplanes.\nWall street is not expecting a mixed\nmarket for railroad' shares during the\nreconversion period because in the\nreadjustments that must he made\nfrom the all-time high wartime earn-\nings all railroads are in the same\nboat. For 1938. the last full year\nbefore the second World war started,\ngross earnings of the railroads were\n$3,565,000,000. For 1944 they were\nat a n*w all-time high of $9,436,000.-\n000. The figures just published for\nthe fl\u2019St half of this jeer are $4,699.-\n000.000 against $4 636.000.000 for the\nlike period of 1944.\nGermany surrendereed on May 6\nfollowed by the first big cancelations\nof war orders and today's earnings of\nseveral railroads for July show whu\nis going on. Baltimore A- Ohio reports\nfor July gross of $31,955,000 against\n$34,606,000 so. 1944 New York Cen\ntral $56,095,000 against 860.797,000.\nJapan asked for peace on August\nSales in 1O\u00bb a H gh Low Close Chg\n1 US Leather 34 34 34\n2d U S Lines 1.3 ft 11ft 4\n10 US Pi pea Hon .48 47ft 47ft- ft\n1 US Play Cd ..52 52 52\n12 U S Plywood 36 1 4 pft _\nIS U S Rea! Simp 2ft 5 4- ft\n31 U S Rubber Ci ft <4 ft bast ft\nH VS 9 R A M 63 ft 62 ft ft\n1 Do pf Mft \u00ab4ft 84ft ft\nM US Steel 71 70ft 70ft\u2014 ft\n12 Dn o f *4 ft 13 ft 24 ft\nHU* Toh 24 ft 2 ft I4ft+ ft\n3 \u2019\u201cn ted Stock a 4 a\n9 United Sir* A 7ft 7 7 ft\n1 Do pt tog ft 10sft lO\u00dfft\u2014 jft\n1 Un.v-Cy Stl !7ft 17ft 17ft- ft\n.10 Univ Lab pf 45 45 45\n1O Univ L Toh pf l<4 144 184\n3 Univ Pct 2>ft 25ft 25ft\nV\n5 Van Sonu 14ft ft 14 ft\n2 Van Raxalte 34 .34ft 39 ft J\n11 Ver-Ca .1 Si 4 id id\n2 Viek Chern #1 .3! 51\n4 Vic Uh Wks 29 ft 291, 29 ft-\n1 Va-Caro Chain sft sft sft\n.50 Va E! 4Pp p* 12\u2019 121 121 ft\n2 Virginian R$ 30ft 50ft 50ft-r ft\nW\n3 Waldorf Sye 15ft 15 1, ft\n2 Walgreen Co 34ft 84ft 34 ft r ft\n1 Wal (H> GAW t* do b(l 3\n1 Do pf 19 ft 19ft 19ft- ft\n30 Walworth Co 12ft 12ft 12ft ft\n3 Ward Raking 4 12ft 12ft J2ft ft\n2* Dn R Ift Ift -ft ft\nDo pf Mft *3 ft 45ft\u2014 ft\n40 Warne. B-o* P 17ft 17 4 17ft\n9 Warren Hl* 4 P .37 36ft .37 1\n5 Wftrren P'et IP 19ft 19ft 1\n1 Wash Gas ll.t !9ft IV, igft 1\n1 Waah Gat Lt 27 ft 27 ft 27 ft ft\nS Waukesha .Motor 21 ft 21 ft 2t ft ft\n1 Wayne Pump 3* ft 38 ft 49 ft\n35 Webeier Toh n\u00bbft pft l\u2018\u00bbft ft ft\n3 Wesson DAS *9ft 28 ft 28ft\nU We-t Ind 3< 3\u00ab jS's ml u\n..3OW#at P E A H\u00bb7 I'M 107 1\nJO Do 7pf ..115 115 115\n3a Went P Poe pf .114 ft IHft 114 ft ft\nWVa PSP 3<)ft ,30ft- ft\n26 Do pf 11Oft 1104 HOU\n7 WaetW\" At U 28ft 25\u2019, 25ft\u2014 ft\n4 West Auto 9 47 46ft *7\n17 W Mary! 9ft 9ft ft\nDo 2 pf lift 24ft 24ftt ft\n5 West Pac ..45ft 45 45 ft\nDo pt M V. Mi ft\n10 W\u2019 UT A 47ft 47 47 ft\n4 1 West Air Or 52 Uft 3'l\n63 West Elec 14 ft 15 ft ;sft ft\n.2\u00ae De of 44 \u00bb3ft 44 ft\nI WeMvaco Ch! .33 7. 33 ft\n01 Do of to|^ ins 188 ft\nDo 4ft pf 105 105 105\n11 Wheeling Steel 3* ft 39ft 39ft\u2014 ft\n56 Do pr pf Mft 9g 9\u00abft- 2ft\n33 White Motor \u00bbft 32ft 33ft. Ift\nu White Sen M\u00ab h isft lift lift, ft\n4 Do pr pt 34 ft 14 34ft* ft\n23 WlllyeOverlgnd *4 ft 23ft ?3ft ft\n73 Wilson 4 Co 15ft lift lift ft\nM nod ward Iron 79 ft ?\u2019ft *9 ft IL\n33 Wenlworth F W 45ft 45ft 45ft ft\n1 Worthing PSM \u00bb7 s\u00abft 54 ft\n1 Do cv pt pt It 3.1 3.1 ft\n2 Do or of 43 92 91 J\n20 Wright Aerd 42 31 M ft\nV\nt Tgla 4 Twna .41 4> 4J\n25 York Core iSft \u20197ft 19ft ft\n9 Yeung SAW 35ft 21st 25\nM Youngst Sb T 52ft 51 ft 52ft\nJO Dn pf \u201905% 105 ft\n15 Young* RD 2d 25ft 2\u00ab -r ft\nZ\n6 Zen th Radio 38ft 38 <1 1\nZoom Prod j\nYBy the Associated Press, August 23)\nPlants and shipyards throughout\nthe country continued to scale down\n1 heir pay rolls yesterday, but evi\ndence appeared that many former war\nworkers were in no great hurry to\nobtain jobs in private industry.\nAn Associated Press survey showed\nfar more than 1.000.000 persons al\nready released because of war con\ntract terminations, and brought int\u00ae\nfocus these significant high lights:\u2014\n1. Reluctance on the part of som\u00ae\nto accept jobs paying less than war\nplants.\n2. While long lines formed at Unit\ned States employment service and\nstate unemployment compensation of\nfices in some cities, others reported\njobs waiting for applicants who did\nnot appear immediately.\n3. Many women and aged men who\ntook war jobs for the duration only\nwere not in the labor market, and.\n4. Former war workers either were\ntaking long-anticipated vacations or\nwere standing by until the job they\nwant shows up in reconverted indus\ntries.\nWhile a true picture of the number\nreleased and quickly absorbed by pri\nvate industry was impossible because\nof fluctuating conditions, a relatively\nheavy demand for workers in food\nand genera) merchandise stores aw\nwell as in service establishments was\nnoted.\nAt rhe same time, some Indication\nwas seen that a start was being made\non the restoration of prewar services.\nAt San Francisco, instalation of dial\ntelephones was resumed. Meat and\nsoap salesmen again were eoliciting\norders in Boston.\nAnd with gasoline rationing eiimi\nnared. operators of roadside lunch)\nstands were reopening to take care\nof motorists.\nFrom some quarters cam\u00ae state\nment* that too much ado was being\nraised over reconversion unemploy\nment. Charles R. Baird regional OPA\nchief at San Francisco, said, \"Pessi\nmistic predictions of widespread un\nemployment in the immediate postwar\nperiod are inconsistent with nation\nwide demand for consumer goods.\u201d\nIn Chicago. William H. Spencer,\nregional WMC director, said 100.000\njobs were available against 85.000 war\nplant layoffs.\nIn Connecticut, where 56 000 have\nbeen laid off. State War Manpower\nCommission Director William J, Fit*--\ngerald predicted \u201csix or seven years\nof the best peacetime prosperity when\nreconversion is fully achieved.\u201d\nMore than 4000 jobs were available\nin stores, garages and sales and serv\nice organizations in Kansas City ye\u00ae-\nterday. but a check showed many\nworkers were turning them down be\ncause the wage was lower than that\nthey received in war plants.\nILLINOIS CENTRAL\nRAILROAD SEIZED\nTruman Acts to Block Strike\nOn Important Line\u2014Juris\ndictional Conflict Is Blamed\nfor Impasse\nWashington. Aug. 23 \u2014(APi-Gov-\nernment seizure of the Illinois Central.\nrailroad was authorized tonight by\nPresident Truman. The Office of De\nfense Transportation will take over\nthe road, which had been threatened\nwith a strike at midnight.\nThe dispute involved promotions,\nstemming from a jurisdictional con\nflict with the Brotherhood of Locomo\ntive Engineers.\nAn a I!-da; meet ing called by Re\nconversion Director John W. Snyder\nat the President\u2019s request had failed\nto gain any settlement of the dispute.\nA stoppage in the railroad industry\nat this time is unthinkable. Presi\ndent Truman said when he signed th\u00ae\nseizure order, the White House re\nported.\nTh* White House order did not de\nfine rhe legal authority for the seisur\u00ae\nbut it apparently was on the ground\nthat the dispute interfered with ef\nfective transition to a peacetime econ\nomy.\nThe President, in an executive or\nde Auguai 18. empowered the War\nl>abor board to consider disputes now\nthat interfered with the transition\nwar-Interrupting disputes.\nboard orders.\nI<*. after which th.ra was wholeula\ncancelation by the government ct its\n\u00bbai orders. It is reasonable therefore\nto expect that, the decline in raii -oad\ngross for August will be larger thin\nfor July Kith the decline from the\nwartime high continuing until some\nthing like a peacetime level has been\nestablished.\nIt is true that for the last four\ndays of lasi week railroad stocks had\na \u25a0\u2018ubstantlai rally. But that was rn\nhave been expensed purely on tech\nnical g--ound\u00ab. Following Japan's re\nquest for peace on the 10th. up to a\n\u00abeek ago today rails had a net de.\nme of gt; points while industrial*\ndeclined only MU points, and th\u00bbn\nstarted las! week's advance to a new\nrecovery high. At last \u00abMk'i rlo*.\ning, rails still have to gain consider,\nable ground before going thr\ntheir June 25 recovery high.\nAtchison was outstanding among\nthe ail. for strength. That com.\npant s July ex nings reported todae,\ninflecting continued heavy shipment*\nof war S'tnnlies to the Pacific coast,\nsit. gross at SSI 422.000 against $40,.\n838.D00 g year ago.\nR I- BARN\u2019 M.\nTREASURY EMPLOYES\nON FIVE-DAY STATUS\nWashington. Aug. 25\u2014(AP)\u2014Mora\nthan 90.000 treasure dAparrmant\nin Washington and in the held\nno on a Avo-day. 40-hour work-week\neffective tomorrow.\nAnnouncing this today. Secretary\ninson said the reduction in hours\nfrom the present work-week of six\ndays and IS hours was taken to con\nform to President Truman advocacy\nof a shorter week for federal em\nployes.\nEARNINGS\nOl G ATE-PALMOt.iI E-PEET\nJersey City. X. J. Aug. 23\u2014<AP1\u2014\nColgate-Palmolive Peel company re\nported today prof): of 33 192.547 r>r\nIt <9 a common share, for the fl-st\nhalf of IMS. compared with 33.140.234.\nor 11 tn a share, for the 1944 similar\nperiod.\nTHOM I\u2019BO> PRODFCTh\nCleveland. Aug. 23\u2014(API\u2014Thomp\nson Products. Inc., today reported eon\nsollated net income for all companies\nof 11.232.356 for the flret six months\nof 1945. equal to 33 06 per common\nshare, compared with 5t.346,030. or\n34.71 par share, in the like period es\n1944.\nFossils are the petrified remains of\nplants or animals that Hved at some\npast period of the earth* history.\n13","height":"25905","width":"19320"}}
